Index no.: 68734 | Wine dataset | Classification problem

1. Introduction

Dataset description:
These data are the results of a chemical analysis of wines grown in the same region in Italy but derived from three different cultivars. The analysis determined the quantities of 13 constituents found in each of the three types of wines.

Target variable:
wine cultivar/type (variable: class)

Features:
13 constituents/components such as color intensity, % of Alcohol, Magnesium etc.

Problem description:
to classify (classification problem) the type of Wine (one of three avaliable), based on its attribues/features.

# Histograms for each variable
def create_hists(kde=True):
    f, axes = plt.subplots(2, 7,figsize=(15,10), sharex=False)
    sns.distplot(data["class"] , color="skyblue", ax=axes[0, 0],kde=False)
    sns.distplot(data["Alcohol"] , color="olive", ax=axes[0, 1],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Malic acid"] , color="gold", ax=axes[0, 2],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Ash"] , color="teal", ax=axes[0, 3],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Alcalinity of ash"] , color="plum", ax=axes[0, 4],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Magnesium"] , color="tomato", ax=axes[0, 5],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Total phenols"] , color="steelblue", ax=axes[0, 6],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Flavanoids"] , color="cyan", ax=axes[1, 0],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Nonflavanoid phenols"] , color="lightgreen", ax=axes[1, 1],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Proanthocyanins"] , color="indigo", ax=axes[1, 2],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Color intensity"] , color="salmon", ax=axes[1, 3],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Hue"] , color="red", ax=axes[1, 4],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["OD280/OD315 of diluted wines"] , color="purple", ax=axes[1, 5],kde=kde)
    sns.distplot(data["Proline"] , color="grey", ax=axes[1, 6],kde=kde)
    plt.show()
    plt.tight_layout()

Summary/Conclusions

General summary:
The main problem of this report was to predict type of wine based on its attributes.
To predict the type of wine, I have built a classifier using machine learning techniques.
Built algorithm is able to predict the type of wine (1 of 3 types) with 97% precision.

Technical notes
Used libraries: pandas, numpy,scikit-learn,matplotlib,seaborn.
Time to run whole code: ~3 minutes
Random state: 101

EDA summary
13 features were loaded to the analysis and 1 target variable (multilabled).
Provided wine datasets was clean. It had no missing values, no false values. There were no outlieres/anomalies.
Descriptive statistics such as max,min,mean,std etc. were calculated, also basic visualizations such as Histograms were created to ensure the tidyness and corectness of the dataset.
Dataset had only 178 observations. Target variable is balanced.
All values of the features seems to have sensible / logic distributons
There are no negative values or zeros.
Heatmap showing Pearson's correlation between variables and target variable was created.
Based on insights from Heatmap - 3 variables were dropped due to high correlation with target variable.
Additionaly, a scatter plot showing possitive correlation between Color Intensity and Alcohol % was created.

Pre-processing summary
Data was standardized by removing the mean and scaled to unit variance on features.
Also three the most correlated variables with target variable were dropped from modeling part - in order to avoid overfitting.
Test size was choosed to be 40% of initial dataset.
Random State was choosed to be 101.

Modelling summary
3 models were choosed to modeling part: k-nearest neighbors (KNN), Logistic Regression, Random Forest.
Predictions were made on those 3 models with default parameters. After that the "worst" performing model was choosed to hypertune its parameters.
The "worst" model was choosed in order to ensure that there is no overfitting.
Model which was choosed as final was Random Forest Classifier (RFC)
After tuning parameters of random forest classifier it results was significantly better.
Random forest classifier itself tends avoid overfitting situation.
The final model had prediction strength of precision: 97%, recall: 97%, f1-score:97%.
Those results are very high because of the low complexity of the initial data.
